spanGrp.span: "Pear Story"; transcribed by SI, checked with ER. OK, but translation has to be finished! updated by WI for DoBeS project in yulz 2013
sounds like /gao a/, but both C and E say it is (or should be) just /gao/
he takes off the berries, he takes off the berries, ? little tsammas which are small
ha au huu aake, ha au huu aake, [ha aake ai] au uni ni iinke,
hy haal die bessies af, hy haal die bessies af, ? klein lemoentjies
/au uni/ first translated as 'lemoentjies', but literally this is 'tsammas'
(he) takes (them) off, he puts them in ...
haal af, en hy sit in ...
the dic has /quu/ 'insit', but it is probably [huu] here
if repeated together with the preceding record, there is an OBL marker between /huu/ and /mandjie/
he takes (them) down, takes (them) down, takes (them) down, he puts (them) into the basket
hau huu, au hau, au hau, ha huu mandjiesi,
hy haal af, haal af, haal af, hy sit (hulle) in die mandjie in
either 'take off' or 'put in' is repeated here; check;
I cannot hear an OBL /ng/ here, but it "should" be there before mandjjiesi acc. to C and E
when the basket is full, he put (the berries) into ...
mandjiesi naka ha unna, nou ha huu
mandjiesi naka ha unna no hng huu
toet die mandjie nou vol is, daar sit hy in ...
a sack, he makes (the sack) stand
CHECK: E and C say /ha/ refers to the Boer, not the sack; probably true
checked: C says /ha oo/ - 'sit hom neer'
there comes a child, it comes riding with a thing
[oeke] oba ha sanna, ha [k ha] nari saa na ng gao
daar kom die kind aan, hy kom ry met die ding
sounds again like an OBL after na, but probably not there (checked with C)
check if there is an /ke/ between /ha/ and /nari/; it sounds like it and it would fit here, but it was not repeated by C and E
which one he is going to take
uu dya xae ha si ii,
I think this is /uu dya xae se ii/ where /se/ is pronoun /si/ + /e/ (SI) - 'which one do we take?' - checked, this is wrong interpretation. C says exactly what is translated in fta
C explains the boy checks if he wants to load the basket or the sack with the pears
then he takes up the sack, then he ...
ha nae ii uu xaan, ha,
ha la ii uu xao a ha
toe vat hy sommer die sak, toe hy ...
ER: might be /ii uu/, there is definitely a second click; check with C
E says OBL is maybe not there, but it should be there before /kunisi/; C agrees
elicitation.: /knn ke annaa kike/ 'daar gaan hulle'
a Boer comes from this side, he drags a goat
huunsi hoo ng xaa ha xaia miri,
toe kom daai Boere van die kant af, hy sleep die bok
former fta: die Boer kom van di kant af, he sleep die bok
/-a/ suffix clearly here in the record, but not there in the next; E and C did not recognize any difference; phonetically only??!!
no idea why previsous token is /xai-a/, and this one is just /xai/, for C and E there is no difference at all
he comes and drags the goat past the tsammas
ha saa, ha xai are miri ng au,
hy sleep hom by die tsamas verby
uu a u qxai, (a ha a ha) a ha au huu [...] aake, [au ...]
die man traak nie (met die ander eener), hy traak net met sy bessies
what (did we call them), little tsamas, little tsamas
tyuin xae [gi], au uni, au uni,
hoe (het ons hom genoem), tsamatjies, tsamatjies
C repeats the wirst words as /tyuin guuke xai/ 'wat is dit'
hy sit hom in die sak
E explains: /huu ng xaan/ is 'sit hom in die sak in'. As jy hom uithaal dan s jy /au huu/.
a little Boer comes, he comes and takes the bag, he loads (it)
huunsi uun ha see, ha see ii xaan, ha nao,
die Boertjie kom, hy kom vat die sak, dan laai hy (hom) op
he (???), he rides as a young man
ha ke kama gareki, ha nari, nari nari aa xai dya (oan),
toe ry hy soos n watse jong man
check with C; /ke/ sounds like [si(i)], (...) could be /ann/ 'path'?! last word could also be s.th. different
former fta: hy ry kama stadig, ry, ry, ry soos n jongman wat gaan
then a young girl comes from there, he ....
toe kom n jong meisiekind van voor af, hy ...
SI asked how can E know that she comes from ahead. E: /ki a/ is 'die kant' = 'that place'?
hy (meisie) kom, hy stap so spoggerig
then he looks back, he looks at the girl, he falls down
ku naka ku aang, ku aqe oatyarasi, ku ii, ku tyiin,
toe het hy omdraai en kyk die meisie, hy val (plat), hy l
check second part with C again; /ii/ 'fall' very, very doubtful; might be 'hat'? Checked. It is definitely not 'hoed', it's a word vir 'val hart'
I'd gloss /hoe/ as cpini and /kiin/ as vitr (SI)
die skoene is sommer ook uit
re-check whole record with C! checked /ka uuke auku nga/ die skoene is sommer uit - no idea what /auku/ means
my skoene is uit my voete uit: /ng kauuke nga ng nng ka qxuu/, and /ng ka kxuu nga ng nng ka uu/ - my voete is uit my skoene uit
at (...) speaker says something indifferent, E says /goe/ is what makes sense there, but it sounds different
the tsamma fell out, they filled all the road
die tsammatjie l die helle pat vol
fta by E: en die tsamas l vol in die pat
au anna hngke, hng unna ng ann
aan ng koke naa qhaake saa,
E understands oe ng koke, she says its not ee ng koke (other people). C says clearly [enn kooke] = /aan ng koke/
not sure what is said at /naa/. sounds like i, C says it is not /nee/ 'naby'. The whole sentence was repeated as /enn koke naa qhaake saa/. C says /naa/ is 'daardie' (SI)
came, took up (the tsamma), helped him, he stands up
saa ii uu, saa hui ku, [ku] ku khuuang, [ku]
kom help hulle vir hom, hy staan op
he mssages his legs, he massages his legs
ku uri ku katyhiin, ku uri ku katyhiin,
the other one comes and helps him
/aan/ sound like /ann/, E says it's ann.
this looks for me as if they lifted stones, they put back ...
hoe ng nng knn sommer aa uu ao, knn goe huu
dit lyk vir my hulle tel sommer die klippers op, hulle steek (hulle) in (die sak in)
the stones, they put into the bag
klippers, hulle sit (hulle) in die sak in
ER: really /knn-a/ in SUBJ position? check recording again (if it isn't knn nou), would be a rare example, normally /kinn ke/ is preferred;
C: ja, hulle s nou vir hom: "klim!"
hulle vat die skoene, hulle kama ...
throw away the stones, throw away the stones
aqbe aa aoke, aqbe aa aoke,
gooi die klippers weg, gooi die klippers weg
so that he can ride nicely
E: /knn aa ng/ is die ander mannetjies
qann ee kua a ng qhii
check with C, checked, this is correct.
they go away, they go away
they come, the children, they walk as grown/up men
sanna kike, oeke [sii ng, sii ng] knn dyaqnn xaanxaan
dan kom hulle, die kinders, hulle staap soos groot mane
for "groot mane" you can say "sterk mane"
they look, they look, they go past the grown-up man
hng (sng) aqe, hng (sng) aqe, hng are ng nain,
hulle (...), hulle (...), hulle gaan aan die groot man verby
/hng sinn hng aqe/ 'hulle kom kyk' (C said it once this slowly) > reduced to > /hng sng aqe/ 'hulle kom kyk'
the grown-up man looks at them
toe kyk die ou man ook vir hulle
a knn are ng ki a,
the grown-up man looks, they go by
die grootman kyk hulle, hulle gaan verby
but the grown-up man does not speak
maar die man praat nie n woord nie
lloks at the children, says "these children"
these children pretend to be grown-ups, they go past
tya oeke kxuu xaanxaan, hng naka hng aa nang,
die kinders, hulle spog en hulle gaan huis toe
E is not really sure what is being said here. C repeated exactly what is here.
E does not know what these words mean. C says: /ku naa soo/ toe sit hy (die ou man)
C does not understand what she said here. Sho only understands /aang/
says surely to the other one "look, he is watching".
seker ka ng uu ko, "naaa, kua aqe",
s seker vir daai ander: "sien!, hy kyk"
Ons gaan mre huis toe. (hulle nog n groot plaan maak, om all daai tsammatjies te kry)
check with C. checked. C does not know exactly what these words are. This is what what she made up of it.
